{
  "answer": "**In \"Soul and Body II\"**, the soul returns repeatedly after death to berate the corpse for its earthly sins, culminating in a mutual accountability at Doomsday.[^1] The most uncomfortable line for the body—the one it would least like addressed to it—is the soul's prophecy of inescapable joint torment: \"For you must answer for us both on that great day... But what will you say to the Lord there on Doomsday? ... Then we must together forever endure such miseries as you prescribed for us.\"[^2] This tradition is most worried about the body's indulgence in \"wicked pleasures\" corrupting the soul, dooming both to Christ's final judgment.[^3]\n\n**In the Smṛti tradition** (e.g., Yama Smṛti, Maṇusmṛti, Aṅgirasa Smṛti), the soul is delivered post-death to Yama (god of death) for judgment on karma/dharma violations, often via torments before rebirth.[^4] No verbatim \"soul returns to address body\" exists, but Yama (or equivalents) indicts sinners; the most uncomfortable line (Yama to sage on unrepentant sinners) is: \"so many spikes he swallows upon reaching Yama, the son of Vivasvat.\"[^5] This tradition is most worried about unexpiated sins/caste breaches accumulating as karmic debt, adjudicated by Yama into hellish rebirths.[^6]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch.10 [chapter](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/).\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-7f7247](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-7f7247).\n[^3]: Ibid., [p-00ea0f](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-00ea0f), [p-34bcc7](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-34bcc7).\n[^4]: *Aṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1 [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-3c396a); *Maṇusmṛti*, ch.12 [p-12.21](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-12.21?query=Yama).\n[^5]: *Aṅgirasa Smṛti*, ch.1 [p-3c396a](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-3c396a).\n[^6]: *Maṇusmṛti*, ch.12 [p-a549f5](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-a549f5) to [p-e464cc](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/12/translation/#p-e464cc); *Yama Smṛti*, ch.1 [chapter](/works/unknown-yama-smrti-552f8d/01/translation/).",
